Product name: SALE Daguerreotype Photo Octagonal Union Case Photo of Man c 1860
Description:
**SALE  Price Reduced from 110 to 89
Wonderful octagonal daguerreotype photo case with a photo of a man inside. There is a paper inside that came with this, it had the name Moses Dudley, and most likely is the identification of the man inside. This is in very good condition both the case and the inside - fabric, frame, glass, photo, everything is intact and was well cared for. The outside has a lovely detailed pattern of scrolls and fancy designs.   This image is on both the front and back sides.  
The case also referred to as a Union Case was made by Littlefield, Parsons, & Co. According to the insert which is under the photo, it claims they are "the sole proprietors and only legal manufacturers of Union Cases with the Embracing Riveted Hinge. Patented October 14, 1856 and April 21, 1857."
Dates ca 1860.
This closes securely and the hinges and closure are in nice shape. There are only a couple tiny nicks in the case - which is amazing - please view last photo to view.  The fabric inside is clean and looks pristine as does everything.  The case is made of a thermoplastic used during this time period.
Case in the closed position, measures 2 1/2" x 3".  It is approx 5/8" depth.
The man (Moses Dudley?), has very hand tinted cheeks - almost in a clown like manner. On the other side of the paper that was tucked in the case, besides the name, it has written "Silver Spoons made before Civil War". Don't know anything about the silver spoons! ...  
Lovely antique keepsake.
Enjoy!
